---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "The Emergency Contraception Guide: Plan B, Ella, and the Copper IUD",
    "description": "Learn about the different types of emergency contraception, including levonorgestrel pills (Plan B), ulipristal acetate (Ella), and the copper IUD. Understand timing, effectiveness, and access.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "The Nookie Nook"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is emergency contraception the same as the abortion pill?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Emergency contraception prevents a pregnancy from occurring, primarily by delaying ovulation. It will not end an existing pregnancy and will not harm a developing embryo if you are already pregnant."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many times can I take Plan B?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "There is no limit to how many times you can safely take emergency contraceptive pills. However, because it is a massive dose of hormones, frequent use can cause irregular periods and is less effective than a primary birth control method."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does weight affect how well emergency contraception works?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Research indicates that levonorgestrel (Plan B) may be less effective for individuals weighing over 165 lbs (75 kg). Ella is more effective for higher weights, but may lose efficacy over 195 lbs. The copper IUD is the most effective method regardless of weight."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

export const meta = {
  title: "The Emergency Contraception Guide",
  description: "Understand your options for emergency contraception, from Plan B to the Copper IUD. Learn about timing, effectiveness, weight limits, and side effects.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="The Emergency Contraception Guide"
  description="Understand your options for emergency contraception, from Plan B to the Copper IUD. Learn about timing, effectiveness, weight limits, and side effects."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/emergency-contraception-guide"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Emergency Contraception Guide</h1>
      <p>What to do when Plan A fails: Timing, options, and access.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Whether a condom broke, you missed a few pills, or you had unprotected sex, emergency contraception (EC) is a safe and effective way to prevent pregnancy after the fact. The key to EC is acting quickly, as effectiveness decreases as time passes. Here is a breakdown of your three primary options.</p>

      <h2>1. Levonorgestrel Pills (Plan B, Take Action, My Way)</h2>
      <p>These are the most common emergency contraceptive pills and are available over-the-counter in most pharmacies without a prescription or age restriction.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How it works:</strong> It delivers a high dose of progestin to delay or prevent ovulation. If there is no egg, sperm has nothing to fertilize.</li>
          <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Must be taken within 72 hours (3 days) of unprotected sex, but is most effective when taken within 24 hours.</li>
          <li><strong>Weight Limitations:</strong> Studies suggest it begins to lose effectiveness for individuals weighing over 165 lbs (75 kg).</li>
          <li><strong>Side Effects:</strong> Nausea, fatigue, headache, and changes to your next period (it may arrive early, late, or be heavier than usual).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>2. Ulipristal Acetate (Ella)</h2>
      <p>Ella is a more effective oral option than Plan B, especially as time passes, but it requires a prescription.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How it works:</strong> It is a progesterone agonist/antagonist that delays ovulation.</li>
          <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Can be taken up to 120 hours (5 days) after unprotected sex. Unlike Plan B, its effectiveness does not significantly drop off during those 5 days.</li>
          <li><strong>Weight Limitations:</strong> More effective than Plan B for heavier individuals, but may begin to lose efficacy for those over 195 lbs (88 kg).</li>
          <li><strong>Important Note:</strong> Do not use hormonal birth control for at least 5 days after taking Ella, as they can counteract each other.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>3. The Copper IUD (Paragard)</h2>
      <p>The copper IUD is the most effective form of emergency contraception available, and it provides ongoing birth control for up to 12 years.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How it works:</strong> The copper is toxic to sperm and eggs, preventing fertilization. If fertilization has already occurred, it changes the uterine lining to prevent implantation.</li>
          <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Must be inserted by a healthcare provider within 120 hours (5 days) of unprotected sex.</li>
          <li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> Over 99% effective, making it far superior to any pill.</li>
          <li><strong>Weight Limitations:</strong> None. It is equally effective regardless of body weight.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Choosing the Right Option</h2>
      <p>If you need emergency contraception, consider these factors:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Time elapsed:</strong> If it has been more than 3 days, seek Ella or a Copper IUD.</li>
        <li><strong>Body weight:</strong> If you weigh over 165 lbs, Ella or a Copper IUD will offer much better protection than Plan B.</li>
        <li><strong>Future plans:</strong> If you want highly effective, long-term birth control going forward, having a Copper IUD inserted solves both the immediate emergency and future needs.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-comparison">Back to Birth Control Comparison</a></li>
        <li><a href="/iud-guide-complete">The Complete IUD Guide (Details on the Copper IUD)</a></li>
        <li><a href="/condom-guide-complete">Condom Guide (Preventing future emergencies)</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
